                    <msContents>
                        
                        <summary>
                            <seg type="para"> This single leaf contains a <title>Fragment from a Synaxarion</title>,  
                                which is a collection of hagiographical brief notices for each day of the year. The fragment is related to
                                the so-called Synaxarion of Constantinople for April 3rd and 4th. 
                               In the small portion contained in Add. 4166.23 
                                are mentioned the martyrs Bythonios, Galykos and Illyrios, who are remembered on April 3rd, and there is a portion of 
                                the notice on the martyrs Theodulos and Agathopous, who are remembered on April 4th.</seg>
                            <seg type="para">Dr Erika Elia</seg>
                            
                        </summary>
                        
                        <textLang mainLang="grc"> Greek</textLang>
                        
                        <msItem n="1"> 
                            <locus from="[1]r" to="[1]v"> f. [1]r-[1]v</locus>
                            <title xml:lang="en"> Synaxarion for the month of April, fragment</title>
                            <incipit defective="true">
                        <locus from="[1]r" to="[1]r"> f. [1]r</locus> 
                        <gap> </gap> Ὁ Βυθόνιος εἰς βυθὸν βεβλημένος, τὴν κλῆσιν εὗρεν</incipit>
                            <explicit defective="true">
                        <locus from="[1]v" to="[1]v"> f. [1]v</locus> καὶ τὴν <supplied reason="damage"> πρ</supplied>ὸς οὐρανοὺς πορείαν αὐτῶν</explicit>
                            <note> See, with some differences, <bibl> H. Delehaye, <hi rend="italic"> Synaxarium Ecclesiae Constantinopolitanae 
                                (e codice Sirmondiano nunc Berolinensi)</hi>, Acta Sanctorum 62, Brussels 1902 (repr. 1985)</bibl>, 584-586; TLG 4411.008</note>
